attributeList.attribute: CDC48 has two AAA domains, D1 and D2 that form two stacked hexameric rings with a central channel. Substrate proteins are unfolded, or stripped from partners or membranes, by inserting them into the D1 pore and threading them through the central channel followed by ejection from the D2 pore. The active hexamer is in a stair-case configuration that enables threading to be driven by a hand-over-hand mechanism in which ATP hydrolysis in the subunit at the bottom of the CDC48 spiral triggers the detachment of this subunit from the spiral and induces its reattachment to the substrate peptide at the top.

A type II AAA ATPase that is involved in the dislocation/extraction step of its substrate proteins from cellular structures or multiprotein complexes into the cytosol where they are largely degraded by the proteasome. Required for the destruction of damaged, misfolded and ubiquitinated proteins in the mitochondrion. Under conditions of mitochondrial stress, VMS1 (Q04311) recruits CDC48 and NPL4 and extracts ubiquitinated proteins for proteasomal degradation. May also play a role in endoplasmic reticulum-associated protein degradation (ERAD).
